25|$|Today, originalism {{is popular}} among some {{political}} {{conservatives in the}} U.S., and it is most prominently associated with Justice Clarence Thomas, Justice Neil Gorsuch, the late Justice Antonin Scalia, and the late Judge <b>Robert</b> <b>Bork.</b> Some liberals, such as late Justice Hugo Black and jurist Akhil Amar, have also subscribed to the theory.|$|E
25|$|From 1973 to 1974 {{he served}} as law clerk to Judge Frank M. Coffin, Chief Judge of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the First Circuit, and from 1974 to 1976 was Assistant to the U.S. Solicitor General, <b>Robert</b> <b>Bork.</b> In 1977, President Jimmy Carter {{appointed}} him Director of the Policy Planning Staff at the Federal Trade Commission.|$|E
25|$|On November 11, 1987, Kennedy was {{nominated}} to the Supreme Court seat vacated by Lewis F. Powell, Jr., who {{announced his retirement}} in late June. His nomination came after Reagan's failed nominations of <b>Robert</b> <b>Bork,</b> who {{was nominated}} in July but rejected by the Senate on October 23, and Douglas Ginsburg, who withdrew his name from consideration on November 7 after admitting to marijuana use. Kennedy was then subjected to an unprecedentedly thorough investigation of his background, which he easily passed.|$|E
