25|$|Roberts helped {{organize}} opposition in Oregon to <b>Robert</b> <b>Bork’s</b> U.S. Supreme Court nomination. From 1988 to 1991 {{she was a}} visiting professor in political science at Oregon State University. In 1988, she received recognition from Portland State University, Oregon State University, and Lewis & Clark Law School. She also served on the state's Commission on Higher Education in the late 1980s. In 1992, Roberts was given the award bearing her name from the Oregon Women Lawyers. She earned the E. B. MacNaughton Civil Liberties Award from the ACLU in 2004.|$|R
